# List of categorical columns
categorical_columns = [
'gender', 'SeniorCitizen', 'Partner', 'Dependents', 'PhoneService',
'MultipleLines', 'InternetService', 'OnlineSecurity', 'OnlineBackup',
'DeviceProtection', 'TechSupport', 'StreamingTV', 'StreamingMovies'
]

# Number of rows and columns in the subplot grid
n_cols = 4 # Number of columns (you can adjust as needed)
n_rows = (len(categorical_columns) // n_cols) + (len(categorical_columns) % n_cols > 0)

# Create the subplot grid
fig, axes = plt.subplots(n_rows, n_cols, figsize=(15, n_rows * 4))

# Flatten the axes array for easy iteration (in case the grid has multiple rows)
axes = axes.flatten()

# Loop through each categorical column and create a countplot
for i, column in enumerate(categorical_columns):

# Hide any unused subplots (if the grid size is larger than the number of columns)
for j in range(i + 1, len(axes)):
axes[j].axis('off')

# Adjust layout for better spacing
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
